props.text: Train and use a neural network (NN) right inside holograph.

Click a distribution of points, and move the big point around to see its color change according to the NN's prediction. It sucks. So lets train the NN to predict the color better. PS: I'd start with a linear distribution
Start training and watch the network buzz. Adjust the learning rate and generate more test data as needed.

When new sample is loaded, the coordinates propagate forward through the network to calculate a predicted value corresponding to the color. That is compared with correct value to calculate the 'loss' (error), which then propagates backward through the network and is used to update the parameters so that the error is reduced.
Coordinates are squashed between 0 and 1, and send into the input nodes
Each hidden node adds up each input multiplied by its corresponding connection weight (plus a bias). Then it gets squashed into an 'activation function', and thats the neurons value.
The output node works the same as the hidden nodes. But this 'activation function' keeps the output between 0 and 1.
We then compare the final neurons value (the prediction) with the actual answer using a 'loss function', in this case- BCE. We want to reduce this.

We then calculate how changes to the bias effect the loss. This requires some calculus- you take the derivative of the bias with respect to the loss. We then nude the bias the opposite direction. (Notice how we calculated the dl_dz as an intermediate value. We'll use this later)
We then calculate how changes to a weight effect the loss (also using calculus. This time is where we use dl_dz. Nude the weight in the opposite direction too.

Now, we pull the dl_dz back from the output neuron to calculate how much the bias needs to change in this layer. In this way the errors 'propagate backwards'. Notice we calculated a new dl_dz for this neuron.
Similarly to before, we use the dl_dz to update these weights. And guess what- you just finished training the NN on an a sample!
